<dl id="n54148g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54148g">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54148g"> 148(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cassowary / = thunder <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54148g"><li>FW 263.f2 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ln/lexln.htm#n54148g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ln/l39ln.htm#n54148g">1939</a> <a href="../../flex/la/lexla.htm#f016">&nbsp;fn016</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54148g">MS BL 47478-330</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:309 <a name="lad13" href="../../ff/fdra/lda.htm#lad13">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/la/lad13.htm#n54148g">Draft: II.2&sect;1.13</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Enfin, apr&egrave;s un r&eacute;sum&eacute; des mythes qui racontent comment Kambel et son fils ont c&eacute;l&eacute;br&eacute; pour la premi&egrave;re fois la c&eacute;r&eacute;monie de la pluie, M. Williams sp&eacute;cifie que &laquo;tous leurs accessoires existent encore aujourd&apos;hui dans le ciel ; et la vraie cause de la pluie est que les animaux qui y jouent un r&ocirc;le, wallabies, bandicoots, serpents, petits oiseaux, et le plus important de tous, un casoar, sont baign&eacute;s dans le baquet de Wambuwambu, et en font rejaillir l&apos;eau. C&apos;est <mark>le casoar qui joue le r&ocirc;le principal: son grondement est en r&eacute;alit&eacute; le tonnerre</mark>, et quand il s&apos;agite dans l&apos;eau et y remue son corps maladroit, il fait tomber la pluie sur la terre&raquo;. <br><font color="green">[Finally, after a summary of the myths which tell how Kambel and his son celebrated the rain ceremony for the first time, Mr. Williams specifies that "all their accessories still exist today in the sky; and the real cause of the rain is that the animals that play a role in it, wallabies, bandicoots, snakes, little birds, and most important of all, a cassowary, are bathed in the tub of Wambuwambu, and make it splash water. The cassowary plays the main role: its rumble is actually thunder, and when it shakes in the water and moves its awkward body there, it makes the rain fall on the ground."]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 297</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
